        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">How Boat Loans Work in Australia</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Boat loans in Australia work similarly to car loans — a lender provides funds to purchase the vessel, and you repay the amount plus interest over an agreed term. However, there are some key differences between boat finance and car finance that are important to understand before applying.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">First, boat loan rates are typically slightly higher than car loan rates. This is because boats depreciate differently to cars, are exposed to environmental damage (salt water, UV, storms), and have a smaller resale market. While a quality car holds its value reasonably well, a boat can lose 15-30% of its value in the first year depending on the type and brand. Lenders account for this higher risk with modestly higher interest rates.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Second, loan terms for boats are often shorter than for cars — commonly 3 to 7 years, though some lenders offer up to 10 years for larger or newer vessels. Shorter terms mean higher repayments but less total interest paid and reduced risk of owing more than the boat is worth (negative equity).</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Third, the definition of a boat for lending purposes varies by lender. Some lenders finance the vessel only, while others will include the motor (outboard or inboard), trailer, marine electronics (GPS, sounder, radar), safety equipment, and even covers or canopies as part of the total financed amount. This is important to clarify upfront so you know exactly what your loan covers.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Nik Finance compares boat loan options from across our panel of 130+ lenders, including specialist marine finance providers who understand boat valuations, seasonal purchase patterns, and the specific requirements of marine lending. Whether you are buying a $5,000 tinny or a $500,000 cruiser, we find the most competitive finance option for your situation.</p>
        </section>
